seeker_post: I was reviewing my compensation and saw I got a 3% merit raise in December. I have yet to complete my review. No one told me about the raise. Is it typical for companies to provide raises at the end of the year or in the review period - jan - March. I am hoping what I got isn’t it and I get a cost of living raise. I have always gotten something in the review period.
human_resp_original: In my experience, I also got my raises after a review. However, I don’t know what job circle you are working in. In the current times of 2024, the job market is being hit pretty hard with high interest rates so a lot of businesses are trying to cut back on spending. I really hope that your 3% raise isn’t all you got. Have you tried talking to your coworkers about raises? Perhaps its merely an HR issue, plus it doesn’t make a whole lot of sense to give someone a raise without explaining their performances that reflected said raise.

Text:
I'm really sorry to hear about the challenges you're facing with no-show candidates. It can be incredibly frustrating and disheartening when you're trying to build a team and the people you're counting on to interview don't follow through. Unfortunately, this has become a more common occurrence in many industries, especially with the ease of applying to jobs online and the impersonal nature of digital communication. It's not a reflection of your capabilities as a manager.
 
 It might be helpful to consider confirming the interview a day in advance and perhaps even an hour before the scheduled time. This could help to ensure that the candidate remembers and prioritizes the interview. Additionally, you might want to ask for confirmation of their attendance as part of your scheduling process. Remember, the right candidates those who are reliable and enthusiastic will show up. It's a tough process, but it's important not to lose hope. Keep pushing forward, and you'll find the team members you're looking for. Hang in there!

Text: Hey there! Oh my, it sounds like you're going through a bit of a frustrating experience! 😔 I can totally understand your concern, especially since this is your first time hiring for multiple positions. 🤔 First of all, let me assure you that it's not uncommon for candidates to cancel or not show up for interviews, especially in today's job market. 🙃 It's possible that some candidates may be overwhelmed with other opportunities or may have changed their minds about the position. 🤷‍♀️ However, it's important to remember that you have the power to set boundaries and expectations with your candidates. 💪 You can start by clearly communicating your expectations for the interview process, such as the time and date of the interview, and the consequences of not showing up or cancelling at the last minute. 📝 It might also be helpful to have a backup plan in place, such as having a list of alternative candidates ready to go in case someone doesn't show up. 💡 And don't be afraid to follow up with no-shows to see if they're still interested in the position. 📞 Remember that hiring is a two-way street, and it's okay to be picky about who you choose to bring onto your team. 😊 Good luck, and I hope you find some amazing candidates soon! 🤞

seeker_post:
My boss scolded me for sending an invoice to the wrong email address (same person) The client have 2 companies, one main work and the other one is her side hustle. I was scolded for sending an invoice to her main work email and the invoice was for her other company.

In my defense, this was never communicated with me in the first place. Our system automatically pulled the “main work” email because the side hustle company is new and is not yet registered in our system. Mind you, it’s the same exact name.

I apologized even though I was never informed, because yeah that’s what you do if you need the job lol
human_resp_original: It sucks that you got scolded by your boss unfairly. I personally hate the way jobs work in the corporate “boss to employee” sense because it really takes away self-respect and almost forces you to wear a mask in front of your boss. Your final line saying that what you did was needed to keep the job is a little sad. Did you clarify that you didn’t know and that you weren’t informed about the issue? Maybe if you have the chance you could go speak to your boss again later next week speaking about the situation. Has your boss every scolded you unfairly before? Regardless, I hope that this isn’t a repeating pattern and you don’t deserve that type of treatment.

seeker_post: I've been applying to many and got a handful of interviews. There's one interview that was promising, but I didn't hear back from them. I do have a degree in film, but it's not getting me anywhere. I kept getting offered to work for experience. My brother got me a job at a factory and I start this Thursday. It's okay looking, but I don't care about the job. My parents are happy for me. I just don't give a shit about my new job. Has anyone been in situation before?
human_resp_original: Hey dude, just treat this factory job as an “inbetween job.” Tons of people do that, and there are also tons of people that do jobs to just make ends meet, so don’t worry about it. Based off your tone though, you seem to be apathetic about your situation. Do you feel down about the other previous interviews you had? Regardless, I think taking a more optimistic approach to your situation would be more helpful. If you don’t care about your new job, then why are you taking it then? Do you need the money from this whole new factory job? What value does this new job bring to you and do you value that type of value? Maybe a first step is to realize and recognize what you value in a job and if this upcoming job adds no value beyond money, then just treat it as an inbetween job and look elsewhere while you work there.

seeker_post: So I am the youngest one at my job (20sF) My favorite co worker (50sF) is like my "work mom", she has kids my age and we get a long vey well. I go to her for advice etc, she is awesome. Recently, She broke up with her BF of many many years. She talked about him constantly. They seemed really in love but he broke her heart. She is so sad and I just feel horrible. Esp bc its near the holidays, and I don't want to see her down. She told me some of the story but I am not going to push for details because I dont want to upset her further. I can tell shes not herself. Being sad at work IS THE WORST! What is an appropriate way I can cheer her up or show her love? We are close, but still.. coworkers, you know? A gift? Pick up some of her work for her, help her out? I just want her to know she is supported.
human_resp_original: Hi! First off, what you are doing right now is so thoughtful and kind. Your coworker is quite lucky to be working with you. In the face of having a heartbroken friend, the most important step to take is to just “listen” and “be present.” Sometimes, people who are grieving like to be alone as well so you have to use your best judgment on how “close” you should be with them. I super respect how you didn’t “push for details,” your emotional intelligence and empathy shined through that restraint. The one thing I don’t disagree with is your coworker boundary. Being a coworker or not doesn’t and shouldn’t stop you from considering them a friend, and I wouldn’t worry about that fact whenever you are trying to cheer someone up. In my opinion, I would go out to grab some grub and catch a movie with them. Maybe don’t directly mention their break up while hanging out with them too. I got this, I hope your coworker friend feels better.

seeker_post: What to do If your boyfriend got caught on creating fake account just to follow girls out there, what will you do? Is that consider cheating?
human_resp_original: Hey. I can tell you're feeling stressed and anxious and I want to help. A couple questions arise from your inquery. Is this currently happening to you? And how exactly did you find out? These questions are important since they would shape what course of action you should take. Whenever or not this is considered "cheating" is a whole different can of worms. Sterotypical instances of cheating are usually having romantic gestures/moments with another person. Therefore, I wouldn't necessarily call it cheating, but this is definietly a red flag. In my opinon, I think clear communication is key. In your situation, I would present the situation in front of them in a calm yet serious manner (especially if this matter is bothering you). Once you presented the sitaution, you must clearly express what you truly feel about whats going on. Make sure to be truthful about what you say so that they get the message. Without clear communication, everything is moot. I truly hope that things will work out.

seeker_post: How do you calm the worries? I'm just now encountering my first serious relationship. I'm sure so many people can relate to the anxiety that comes with being in a legitimate relationship for the first time. I try to be confident but sometimes the anxiety gets the best of me and I start having fear over things like: Will he eventually fall out of love with me? Will he look at me one day and decide he doesn't want me or love me? Will it be something that gradually happens?- cheating. I have heard so many stories and I am terrified. That would absolutely break me. I am terrified of someone else catching his interest & it happening. I know one of his coworkers is really toxic and they had history; I have an irrational fear that she'll try things again once she knows we're serious. I'm just so terrified it holds me back. I've been so confident but as of recent, I just have this fear in my mind of these two things happening. How do you quell your worries about these things? :(
human_resp_original: I can see you’re super worried and anxious and you know what, that’s a normal feeling to have when you’re in an invested relationship. In order to calm these worries, communication is key. Talk about your feelings with your partner, and make sure you talk about it in a healthy way (try not to overinvest or incorrectly direct your negative emotions towards them). I’m super neurotic so when it comes to those types of things, I always try to communicate and be as transparent as possible. Talking it out takes out the mental thought rumination that happens in your head. This might not completely quell your worries, but it will likely give you a break. As well, I suggest practicing self-generation of happiness. Being independent and enjoying things beyond your relationship is also very helpful.

Text:
It's completely natural to feel anxious when navigating the uncharted waters of a first serious relationship. The fears you're experiencing are shared by many, and it's okay to acknowledge them. Remember, anxiety often stems from our desire to control the uncontrollable봪ike someone else's feelings or actions. It's important to focus on what you can control: your own thoughts, feelings, and behaviors.
 
 To calm your worries, try to engage in open and honest communication with your partner. Expressing your feelings can help build trust and understanding between you both. Also, consider practicing self-care and mindfulness techniques, such as deep breathing, meditation, or journaling, to manage anxiety.
 
 Building self-confidence is key. Remind yourself of your worth and the unique qualities you bring to the relationship. Trust is fundamental, and while it's challenging, try to trust in your partner's commitment to you.
 
 Lastly, if the anxiety becomes overwhelming, don't hesitate to seek support from friends, family, or a professional counselor who can provide you with tools and strategies to cope with these fears. Remember, you're not alone, and it's okay to ask for help.

Text: Hey there! 🤗 I totally understand how you feel - it's completely normal to have these fears and anxieties in a new relationship, especially when it's your first serious one. It's natural to feel vulnerable and unsure, but remember that these feelings are temporary and can be managed with time and effort. Firstly, let's address the fear of your partner falling out of love with you. It's important to remember that love is a choice, and it's not something that can be lost overnight. If your partner has chosen to be with you, it's likely that they value and care for you deeply. It's okay to have moments of doubt, but try not to let those doubts consume you. Instead, focus on the positive aspects of your relationship and the things that bring you joy and happiness together. Regarding the fear of cheating, it's important to remember that you can't control your partner's actions or thoughts. However, you can control how you react to situations and how you communicate your feelings to your partner. It's important to have open and honest communication with your partner about your fears and boundaries. Talk to them about what makes you feel uncomfortable or anxious, and work together to find solutions that make you both feel safe and secure. Lastly, it's understandable that you have an irrational fear of your partner's coworker, but try not to let that fear consume you. It's important to remember that your partner has chosen to be with you, and it's unlikely that they would risk their relationship with you for someone else. Instead of focusing on the negative, try to focus on the positive aspects of your relationship and the things that bring you joy and happiness together. Remember that it's okay to feel scared and anxious in a new relationship, but it's important to not let those feelings hold you back. Take things one step at a time, communicate openly and honestly with your partner, and focus on the positive aspects of your relationship. With time and effort, you can work through these fears and build a strong and healthy relationship. 💕

seeker_post: I love my girl so much. Yesterday, I was helping an old man in our apartment complex while my Girlfriend was housesitting for a friend on the other side of town. As I was entering the complex with him carrying the furniture he needed assistance with. My back seized up, and I almost fell down with the furniture. It hurt to move. Even Hurt to breath. It was an intense pain all through my back. I powered through, made it up into our apartment and found the bed. She called me and asked what happened because she's seen me on the video doorbell and I looked like I was in pain, I explained and she quickly rushed 20 minutes back out to our apartment. She got me a heating pad, fed me pain medicine, massaged my back, even helped me get to the bathroom, and got me food and drink when I needed it. She stayed with me almost the whole evening, (she had to go back to where she was housesitting)I CRIED. So much. I felt so weak and powerless and she cared for me so easily, so naturally. She made sure I was okay, and even with my pained range of motion could easily grab the tv remote or whatever so I wouldn't be bored or thirsty/hungry. She's an absolute goddess. And I needed to share that. Thankfully, the pain subsided and I'm feeling totally fine today!
human_resp_original: Wow, your feelings about your girlfriend are clear as day, I can totally see passionate gratitude coming off you right now. During the first half of the story I was seriously concerned about what happened. But, hearing about how quick your Girlfriend was to reach out, quickly be there and proactively take care of your needs was so CUTE! The way you talk about your girlfriend feels so genuine and loving, it feels really infectious that makes me feel warm and fuzzy. I truly wish more great things for you and your loved ones.

seeker_post: One of my kids is in the first grade.  They started school at the beginning of August.  The teacher sits at her desk basically all day while the kids do worksheets that are overly simplistic even for their young age.  Friday, she sent home progress reports.  The scores just didn't really fit my son's strengths and weaknesses.  A friend that also has a child in the class and I compared notes and the scores for both children were exactly the same-all 19 of them.  So, I'm guessing she just filled this evaluation the same for each student.  What do you think I should do about it?  I don't want to alienate her considering she is my kid's teacher, but this doesn't seem right.  I'm new at this school thing (as a parent) and would love your opinions.  Thanks.
human_resp_original: You’ve got to address your problem directly to the teacher first. Have you ever addressed a concern to the teacher directly? If I were you, I would ask to schedule a meeting with the teacher and talk about your child’s performance to see whenever or not they can justify the home progress reports. How does your child feel about the teacher? Does he feel like he is learning anything new or simulating? If what your saying is true (i.e. solving simple worksheets), then this is a serious issue that requires immediate attention. Education is really important at a young age and shapes how people will learn forever. First, schedule a meeting and then talk with your child privately about how they feel in school academically. And then we can move forward afterward.

Text:
It's completely understandable that you're concerned about your child's education and the approach the teacher is taking. It's important for progress reports to accurately reflect each child's individual abilities and progress, and it's concerning that your son's report doesn't seem to align with his strengths and weaknesses. It's also quite disconcerting that the reports for two different children are identical.
 
 Before taking any action, it might be helpful to gather more information. Consider requesting a meeting with the teacher to discuss your son's progress report. Approach the conversation with curiosity rather than accusation, which can help maintain a positive relationship. You could express your appreciation for her work and then share your observations, asking for clarification on how the evaluations are determined.
 
 If after the meeting you still have concerns, it might be appropriate to reach out to the school's administration for further guidance. Remember, advocating for your child's education is important, and doing so respectfully can lead to better outcomes for everyone involved.

Firstly, I would suggest speaking with the teacher directly and sharing your concerns in a respectful and open-minded way. seeker_post:
I realize that the two aren't mutually exclusive. I have a lot of good friends and family who are Christian, and a few friends who are gay. I don't really have anything against either group. It's just that I'd find it much easier being supportive of a gay son than a Christian son. I'm straight, but I can understand being in love, and I think I could deal with the first time my son brings home a boyfriend if he turns out to be gay. As an atheist, though, I can't understand believing in God, and I think if he turns out to be Christian, it would be hard for me to be supportive. He'd have more community support as a Christian, but I feel like it would be harder to connect with him myself.
Is this selfish?
human_resp_original: I think you are asking the wrong question on whether or not you think it is selfish to think the way you are thinking. In my opinion, the capacity to connect with others doesn’t require you to completely understand their beliefs or preferences. When you connect with someone, you see beyond all of those biases and connect through similarities and differences. Supporting a family doesn’t require us to understand them. I think family should be shrouded in unconditional love, especially if those conditions don’t necessarily harm another. Therefore, to answer your question, I do think it is selfish to consider yourself not supportive of your hypothetical son’s religious beliefs. Regardless of what they believe in, you should support the things that make someone else happy unless those things are things that harm themself or others. However, maybe your definition of supportive is different from mine.
